Gents:

I would think that the value of the in-addr PTR record
must be a name that can be inserted in the domain controlled by
the organization.  Without this, the naming cannot be symmetric.

For example, if Ohio State used 
0.0.146.128.in-addr.arpa.	IN	PTR	OHIO-STATE

they would be unable to provide the forward mapping from the
name to the net number.  (ohio-state is an invalid DNS name).

One would think that the best that could be done is to place
the network name as close to the top of the "forward" domain
name space as the organization is allowed.  So, in the
case of Ohio State, perhaps
ohio-state.ohio-state.edu	IN	PTR	0.0.146.128.in-addr.arpa.

Frankly, I think their current naming (net.ohio-state.edu) is better!
It certainly seems more meaningful.  It is fairly intuitive.


Bob

